issue.title: Replace 'Include Internal Transfers' checkbox with multi-select transaction type filters
issue.body:
This PR enhances the Reports pages by replacing the simple "Include Internal Transfers" checkbox with comprehensive multi-select transaction type filters, providing users with granular control over which transaction types to include in their financial analysis.

## Changes Made

### User Interface Improvements
- **Spending Reports**: Now shows a "Spending Types" multi-select filter with options for `expense`, `transfer`, and `asset-allocation` (defaults to `expense` only)
- **Income Reports**: Now shows an "Income Types" multi-select filter with the same options (defaults to `income` only)  
- **Main Reports**: Shows a "Transaction Types" filter with all four options (defaults to `income` and `expense`)

### Technical Implementation
- Updated `reportsService.ts` with overloaded method signatures to support both the new `selectedTypes: string[]` parameter and legacy `includeTransfers: boolean` for backward compatibility
- Enhanced filtering logic to properly handle transfer transactions based on amount direction (positive amounts for income, negative for expenses)
- Integrated with existing `MultiSelectFilter` component for UI consistency with the Transactions page

### User Experience Benefits
- **More Control**: Users can now precisely choose which transaction types to include rather than just toggling transfers on/off
- **Better Defaults**: Each page has sensible defaults (Income shows income by default, Spending shows expenses by default)
- **Consistent Interface**: Uses the same multi-select pattern as the Transactions page for familiar user experience
- **Flexible Analysis**: Users can now include asset allocation transactions for investment tracking

## Before vs After

**Before**: Simple checkbox labeled "Include Internal Transfers"
**After**: Multi-select dropdown with all transaction types and appropriate defaults per page

![Multi-select filter in action](https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/c4f4cc12-1094-418f-8001-065d94a5f98d)

The screenshot shows the Income Reports page with the new "Income Types" filter expanded, displaying all available transaction types with "income" and "transfer" selected, resulting in a comprehensive view of income sources.

## Testing
- ‚úÖ All existing tests pass (87 test suites, 463 tests)
- ‚úÖ Build completes successfully  
- ‚úÖ Verified filtering works correctly with sample data
- ‚úÖ Confirmed totals update properly when transaction types are added/removed
- ‚úÖ Tested backward compatibility with existing method calls

Fixes #473.

issue.title: timeshift-gtk unnecessarily waits too much when creating or removing btrfs backup successfully
issue.body:
**Describe the bug**
timeshift-gtk unnecessarily waits too much when creating or removing btrfs backup successfully (even after the backup is done making or removing)

**To Reproduce**
Steps to reproduce the behavior:
1. Go to timeshift-gtk
2. Click on Create Backup
3. Backup creates but you wait something like 20 more seconds unnecessarily

**Expected behavior**
Wait time shouldn't be that long after successful creation or removal.

**Screenshots**

![Image](https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/f684f2a4-5cef-4c26-8687-1f8dd2e42ba6)

![Image](https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/6ce59a82-1927-4a9f-9d06-012b4f270da8)

(15 or so seconds after successful creation)
![Image](https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/2b5bfb02-60ad-4c05-8d24-0d7e973db5a2)

(15 or so seconds after successful removal)
![Image](https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/35ed32ca-48bc-47a0-ad06-0d3e2947ca89)

**System:**
 - Linux Distribution Name and Version: [Ubuntu Plucky]
 - Desktop [KDE]
 - Application Version [24.06.6]

issue.title: `cargo publish` stripping `hints` section from Cargo.toml

labels.name: S-triage
labels.description: Status: This issue is waiting on initial triage.

issue.body:
### Problem

We recently added `hints.mostly-unused = true` to several of the aws-sdk-rust crates to improve compilation time (ex: [aws-sdk-ec2](https://github.com/awslabs/aws-sdk-rust/blob/4fcc47b2babc2d3c78c9e7861d75328a6315fba5/sdk/ec2/Cargo.toml#L146-L147)). A [user reported](https://github.com/awslabs/aws-sdk-rust/issues/113#issuecomment-3182336182) that compiling with the new `-Zprofile-hint-mostly-unused` option did not improve their compilation times and that they did not see a `hints` section when looking at the crate in the Cargo cache. 

When looking at the [published source](https://docs.rs/crate/aws-sdk-ec2/1.158.0/source/Cargo.toml#149) on docs.rs (which I assume is the same as that on crates.io?) I also do not see a `hints` section. Running `cargo publish --dry-run` and looking at the generated package in `target/package` I can confirm that the `hints` section is removed from the package by the publish command.

Running `cargo +nightly publish --dry-run` does include the `hints` section in Cargo.toml 

### Steps

```sh
git clone --depth 1 https://github.com/awslabs/aws-sdk-rust.git;
cd aws-sdk-rust/sdk/ec2;

# Finds hints
cat Cargo.toml | grep hints;

# If you add +nightly here all works as expected
cargo publish --dry-run;

# Does not find hints (unless you add +nightly in the line above)
cat ../../target/package/aws-sdk-ec2-1.158.0/Cargo.toml | grep hints;
```

### Possible Solution(s)

I suspect that `cargo publish` is stripping out unrecognized sections in Cargo.toml, and we are not publishing with nightly and the `-Zprofile-hint-mostly-unused` option. This should likely be more permissive in allowing sections through. 

### Notes

_No response_

### Version

```sh
# Local testing
$ cargo --version
cargo 1.89.0 (c24e10642 2025-06-23)

$ cargo +nightly --version
cargo 1.91.0-nightly (840b83a10 2025-07-30)


# Actual publishing
$ cargo --version
cargo 1.86.0 (adf9b6ad1 2025-02-28)
```

issue.title: tests: make uio test regex work with musl
issue.body:
musl-libc handles the `pwrite` calls differently than glibc, making the uio tests fail. Using glibc, there are separated `pwrite` and `pwritev` calls, however musl uses only `pwritev2` for both `pwrite` and `pwritev`.

To account to this difference, change the verifying regex in way to match both glibc and musl outputs.

Closes #346

**What kind of device or service you would like to see an adapter for?**
Toshiba Air Condition

**Is an official API including documentation is available?**
No -  but an app for iOS and Android
https://play.google.com/store/apps/details?id=com.toshibatctc.SmartAC

**Are other libraries for an integration available?**
Yes, but not in Javascript
https://github.com/KaSroka/Toshiba-AC-control

**Is this device already integrated in other Smart Home systems?**
Home Assistant
https://github.com/h4de5/home-assistant-toshiba_ac

**Is this device already integrated in homebridge? Might the ham adapter together with the homebridge plugin be sufficient?**
No - theres a midea-Adapter, but toshiba devices seems to be incompatible

**Additional context**
I managed to get the Home Assistant Integration working and importet the devices into iobroker via the HASS-Adapter.
But i need to maintain an actual Home Assistant Installation, which adds a lot of complexity - native iobroker-adapter would be better.
